Part I - FordGoBike-tripdata-2019-02¶

by Mahmoud Jawabreh¶

Introduction¶

Introduce the dataset

This dataset has around 183,000 entries and 16 variables, start and end of the trip aswell the trip duration in seconds. It contains data about the station details, station id, name, longitude and latitude for the start and end station, bike id, user type, member details such as birth year and gender and finally 'bike_share_for_all_trip' specifying whether the trip was part of a bike share program.

I will create a function to reduce the code for cleaning the dataframe from duplicate values and drop rows that contain NaN values

In [2]:
def clean_dataframe(df):

    # counts duplicates and NaN values 
    duplicate_count = df.duplicated().sum()
    nan_count = df.isna().sum().sum() 

    print(f"Number of duplicate rows: {duplicate_count}")
    print(f"Number of NaN values: {nan_count}")

    if duplicate_count > 0:
        df = df.drop_duplicates().reset_index(drop=True)
        print("Duplicates removed.")
    
    if nan_count > 0:
        df = df.dropna().reset_index(drop=True)
        print("Rows with NaN values removed.")
    
    return df

Conclusions¶

Throgh the visualizations across univariate,bivariate, and multivariate we found that:

Most of the users are subscribers.

Subscribers usually tend to take shorter trips while customers take longer trips.

Older people take longer trips, but age has weak correlation with duration.

Customers don't attend shared programs
